<author><name><![CDATA[zcorpan]]></name></author>
<updated>2009-03-13T08:46:34+00:00</updated>
<id>https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=163&amp;p=4863#p4863</id>
<link href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=163&amp;p=4863#p4863"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[I'm skeptical of all these narrowly defined tags]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=163&amp;p=4863#p4863"><![CDATA[
We can't make &lt;img&gt; a container element because of legacy -- all pages on the Web that use &lt;img&gt; today would break. We can't introduce &lt;image&gt; as a container element, either, because there are pages out there that have &lt;image&gt; and expect to be treated as &lt;img&gt;.<br /><br />If you want rich fallback for images, use &lt;object&gt;. If the image is purely decorative, you could use CSS3 generated content:<br /><br /><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: </dt><dd><code>&lt;h1&gt;Foo &lt;strong&gt;bar&lt;/strong&gt; baz&lt;/h1&gt;</code></dd></dl><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: </dt><dd><code>h1 &#123; content:url&#40;foo.png&#41; &#125;</code></dd></dl><br /><br /><blockquote><div><cite>Ritz wrote:</cite><br />I have discovered that &lt;canvas&gt; already works the way I was proposing &lt;img&gt; or &lt;image&gt; might work. Right now that code validates, but I do notice some language that discourages the kind of use I've just implemented:<br /></div></blockquote>I think it's equally discouraged as using &lt;img&gt; here, but currently the alternatives that work cross-browser aren't great either, so I would say that for now it's fine.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4">zcorpan</a> — Fri Mar 13, 2009 8:46 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
