<blockquote><div><cite>lyosha wrote:</cite><br />Make it something like this and we'll be happy:<br /><br /><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: </dt><dd><code>&lt;style&gt;<br />h1 &#123;background-image: url&#40;'chocolate.png'&#41; no-repeat;&#125;<br />h1 span &#123;display: none;&#125;<br />&lt;/style&gt;<br /><br />&lt;h1&gt;&lt;span&gt;The chocolate headline&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;</code></dd></dl><br /></div></blockquote><br /><br />That doesn't work for screen readers that process CSS correctly, according to <a href="http://www.alistapart.com/articles/fir/" class="postlink">http://www.alistapart.com/articles/fir/</a>. See &quot;Results&quot; and &quot;Analysis&quot;. Screen readers, when behaving the way most do, will simply ignore the information altogether when you use <span style="font-style: italic">display: none;</span>. You might as well use &quot;#&quot; or &amp;nbsp; instead of &quot;The chocolate headline&quot;.<br /><br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div><br />Completely not backwards compatible which is HTML 5's goal. (although there is the &lt;legend&gt; mess which isn't backwards compatible.)<br /></div></blockquote><br /><br />Neither is &lt;canvas&gt;, but it has a fallback mechanism in place. Why not consider the same for &lt;img&gt; or &lt;image&gt;?<br /><br />[EDIT]<br /><br />...Actually, after reading  <a href="http://html5.org/tools/web-apps-tracker?from=2867&amp;to=2868" class="postlink">r2868</a> and experimenting with code similar to this:<br /><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: </dt><dd><code>&lt;!doctype html&gt;<br />&lt;html lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;<br />&lt;head&gt;<br />&lt;meta charset=&quot;utf-8&quot; /&gt;<br />&lt;title&gt;Test&lt;/title&gt;<br />&lt;style&gt;<br />canvas &#123;<br />   background-image: url&#40;'sample.jpg'&#41;;<br />   background-repeat: no-repeat;<br />   display: block;<br />   height: 750px;<br />   width: 75px;<br />&#125;<br />&lt;/style&gt;<br />&lt;/head&gt;<br />&lt;body&gt;<br />&lt;h1&gt;&lt;canvas&gt;I love chocolate!&lt;/canvas&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;<br />&lt;p&gt;Hooray!&lt;/p&gt;<br />&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;</code></dd></dl><br /><br />I have discovered that &lt;canvas&gt; already works the way I was proposing &lt;img&gt; or &lt;image&gt; might work. Right now that code validates, but I do notice some language that discourages the kind of use I've just implemented:<br /><br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div><br />&lt;p&gt;Authors should not use the &lt;code&gt;canvas&lt;/code&gt; element in a<br />   document when a more suitable element is available. For example, it<br />   is inappropriate to use a &lt;code&gt;canvas&lt;/code&gt; element to render a<br />   page heading: if the desired presentation of the heading is<br />   graphically intense, it should be marked up using appropriate<br />   elements (typically &lt;code&gt;h1&lt;/code&gt;) and then styled using CSS and<br />   supporting technologies such as XBL.&lt;/p&gt;<br /></div></blockquote><br /><br />But... this is exactly what I want to do with &lt;canvas&gt;, now. Isn't this better than <span style="font-style: italic">display: hide;</span> or <span style="font-style: italic">text-indent: -999em;</span>?<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=458">Ritz</a> — Thu Mar 12, 2009 8:33 pm</p><hr />
